{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526887"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:27:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:27:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14166"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14166"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.01,0.82,0.02,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6849"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101760"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6849"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14166"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84216"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"898"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9736"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15541"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17789"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18514"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38757"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43498"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44721"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45998"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49902"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101760"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of worsening shortness of breath. She has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes, and ischaemic heart disease. Her regular medications include metformin, ramipril, and atorvastatin. On examination, she appears distressed with a respiratory rate of 28/min. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 160/95 mmHg, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Auscultation of the chest reveals bilateral crackles to the mid-zones. There is pitting oedema to both ankles. The nurse looking after the patient has already initiated oxygen therapy given the abnormal saturations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ECG shows sinus tachycardia with no acute ischaemic changes. Chest X-ray reveals pulmonary oedema with upper lobe diversion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous amiodarone","Intravenous digoxin","Intravenous furosemide","Intravenous morphine","Non-invasive ventilation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute heart failure, specifically acute pulmonary oedema. The initial management should focus on reducing congestion and improving oxygenation. \u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous furosemide\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line treatment in this scenario. It acts quickly to reduce preload by promoting diuresis, thereby alleviating pulmonary congestion and improving symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-invasive ventilation\u003C/strong\u003E (NIV) such as CPAP or BiPAP can be beneficial in acute pulmonary oedema, especially in patients with significant respiratory distress or hypoxia despite oxygen therapy. While it may be considered for this patient given her low oxygen saturation, it typically follows initial medical management with diuretics and nitrates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous morphine\u003C/strong\u003E was traditionally used in acute heart failure for its anxiolytic and venodilatory effects. However, its use is now controversial due to the risk of respiratory depression and potential masking of worsening symptoms. It is no longer recommended as a routine treatment in acute heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous digoxin\u003C/strong\u003E is not a first-line treatment for acute heart failure. It may be considered in patients with atrial fibrillation and rapid ventricular response, which is not the case here. Its onset of action is also too slow for acute symptom relief.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous amiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiarrhythmic drug used primarily for the treatment of ventricular and supraventricular arrhythmias. It is not indicated in this case as the patient is in sinus tachycardia, which is an appropriate physiological response to acute heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initiating furosemide, additional management would likely include oxygen therapy, nitrates (if blood pressure allows), and consideration of non-invasive ventilation if the patient\u0027s respiratory status does not improve. Continuous monitoring of vital signs, urine output, and electrolytes is essential. The underlying cause of the acute decompensation should also be investigated and addressed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Initial management of acute heart failure includes oxygen therapy, diuretics, and nitrates to reduce preload and afterload.","Non-invasive ventilation should be considered in patients with acute pulmonary oedema and respiratory distress.","Morphine should be used cautiously in acute heart failure due to potential respiratory depression."],"references":["European Society of Cardiology. 2021 ESC Guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of acute and chronic heart failure [Internet]. European Society of Cardiology. 2021. Available from: https://www.escardio.org/Guidelines/Clinical-Practice-Guidelines/Acute-and-Chronic-Heart-Failure"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84216"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14166"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84216"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-04T13:27:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-12T17:21:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6849"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101760"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings"